    <text type="letter"> 
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc.03072.002.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener> 
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place">On cars.</name>
                    <date>Mond morn<ptr target="loc.03072_n1"/></date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Dear W. W.</salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Yesterday (Sunday) afternoon) read again with deepest interest the Songs of Parting. I
                keep touching deeper &#38; not before understood tho'ts with my plummet in reading
                you,&#8212;espec. in these solemn hymns of the Infinite. The productions of Homer
                &#38; Milton seem quite boyish in comparison with the profound cosmic epic L. of G.
                It is a refreshing draught to me after the <hi rend="underline">Bafflement</hi> of
                the week in newspapers. Be sure to read Tyndall's<ptr target="loc.03072_n3"/> fascinating long article of
                reminiscences of Carlyle<ptr target="n1065"/> in January <hi rend="underline"
                    >Fortnightly</hi>.</p>
            <closer>
                <salute>With the old love&#8212;</salute>
                <signed>W. S. K.</signed>
            </closer>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc.03072.001.jpg" type="verso"/>
        </body>
